    "configuration": {
      "title": "AtlasMind",
      "properties": {
        "atlasmind.budgetMode": {
          "type": "string",
          "default": "balanced",
          "enum": [
            "cheap",
            "balanced",
            "expensive",
            "auto"
          ],
          "description": "Budget preference for model selection.",
          "markdownDescription": "Budget preference for model selection.\n\nUse `cheap` to keep routing on the lowest-cost acceptable models, `balanced` for the default mix, `expensive` to unlock premium reasoning models, or `auto` to let AtlasMind infer the tier from the task.\n\nExamples:\n- Solo scratchpad or note-heavy work: `cheap`\n- Day-to-day engineering work: `balanced`\n- Architecture reviews, migrations, or ambiguous debugging: `expensive`\n- Shared team workspace with mixed task sizes: `auto`"
        },
        "atlasmind.speedMode": {
          "type": "string",
          "default": "balanced",
          "enum": [
            "fast",
            "balanced",
            "considered",
            "auto"
          ],
          "description": "Speed preference for model selection.",
          "markdownDescription": "Speed preference for model selection.\n\nUse `fast` to bias toward quick-response models, `balanced` for a normal tradeoff, `considered` to allow slower reasoning-heavy models, or `auto` to let AtlasMind choose based on task complexity.\n\nExamples:\n- Tight feedback loops while editing: `fast`\n- General coding and chat: `balanced`\n- Root-cause analysis or long-form planning: `considered`\n- Teams switching between support, coding, and review: `auto`"
        },
        "atlasmind.feedbackRoutingWeight": {
          "type": "number",
          "default": 1,
          "minimum": 0,
          "maximum": 2,
          "description": "How strongly saved thumbs-up or thumbs-down feedback should influence future model routing. Set to 0 to disable the feedback bias.",
          "markdownDescription": "How strongly saved thumbs-up or thumbs-down feedback should influence future model routing. AtlasMind still caps the effect so votes cannot override capability, budget, speed, or provider-health gates.\n\nExamples:\n- Disable feedback-weighted routing: `0`\n- Default slight bias: `1`\n- Stronger but still bounded nudge: `1.5`\n\nUse this when you want feedback to matter more or less without deleting the recorded vote history."
        },
        "atlasmind.localOpenAiBaseUrl": {
          "type": "string",
          "default": "http://127.0.0.1:11434/v1",
          "description": "Base URL for a local OpenAI-compatible model endpoint such as Ollama or LM Studio.",
          "markdownDescription": "Base URL for a local OpenAI-compatible model endpoint such as Ollama or LM Studio. AtlasMind appends the provider-specific chat paths under this base URL.\n\nExamples:\n- Ollama default: `http://127.0.0.1:11434/v1`\n- LM Studio local server: `http://127.0.0.1:1234/v1`\n- Remote self-hosted gateway on a lab network: `http://10.0.0.25:8080/v1`\n\nFor team or scaled deployments, point this at a stable gateway or reverse proxy rather than an individual developer machine."
        },
        "atlasmind.azureOpenAiEndpoint": {
          "type": "string",
          "default": "",
          "description": "Azure OpenAI resource endpoint used for deployment-based chat routing, for example https://your-resource.openai.azure.com.",
          "markdownDescription": "Azure OpenAI resource endpoint used for deployment-based chat routing. This should be the resource endpoint, not a deployment or API path.\n\nExample:\n- `https://your-resource.openai.azure.com`\n\nIn larger environments, keep this aligned with the approved regional Azure OpenAI resource for your team, then manage access with SecretStorage-backed API keys and deployment allow-lists."
        },
        "atlasmind.azureOpenAiDeployments": {
          "type": "array",
          "default": [],
          "items": {
            "type": "string"
          },
          "description": "Azure OpenAI deployment names that AtlasMind should surface as routed models.",
          "markdownDescription": "Azure OpenAI deployment names that AtlasMind should surface as routed models. Use deployment names exactly as they exist in Azure.\n\nExamples:\n- Single deployment: `[\"gpt-4.1\"]`\n- Split by workload: `[\"gpt-4.1-mini\", \"gpt-4.1\", \"o4-mini\"]`\n- Enterprise setup with separate safety-reviewed deployments per capability: `[\"chat-standard\", \"reasoning-premium\", \"vision-approved\"]`\n\nKeep this list intentionally small so only approved deployments appear in routing."
        },
        "atlasmind.bedrock.region": {
          "type": "string",
          "default": "",
          "description": "AWS region used for Amazon Bedrock model invocations, for example us-east-1.",
          "markdownDescription": "AWS region used for Amazon Bedrock model invocations. AtlasMind signs requests for the region you specify here.\n\nExamples:\n- `us-east-1` for common Bedrock availability\n- `us-west-2` for teams standardizing on West US adjacency\n\nIn multi-account or compliance-sensitive setups, choose the region that matches your approved Bedrock access boundary and the models listed in `atlasmind.bedrock.modelIds`."
        },
        "atlasmind.bedrock.modelIds": {
          "type": "array",
          "default": [],
          "items": {
            "type": "string"
          },
          "description": "Amazon Bedrock model IDs AtlasMind should expose as routed models, such as anthropic.claude-3-7-sonnet-20250219-v1:0.",
          "markdownDescription": "Amazon Bedrock model IDs AtlasMind should expose as routed models. Use the full Bedrock model ID, not a friendly alias.\n\nExamples:\n- `[\"anthropic.claude-3-7-sonnet-20250219-v1:0\"]`\n- `[\"anthropic.claude-3-5-haiku-20241022-v1:0\", \"amazon.nova-pro-v1:0\"]`\n\nFor larger organizations, use this as an allow-list so AtlasMind only routes to approved Bedrock models."
        },
        "atlasmind.ssotPath": {
          "type": "string",
          "default": "project_memory",
          "description": "Relative path to the SSOT memory folder. If that path is missing, AtlasMind auto-detects an existing MindAtlas project in the current workspace when possible.",
          "markdownDescription": "Relative path to the SSOT memory folder. AtlasMind expects a safe workspace-relative path and will auto-detect an existing memory folder when possible if the configured path is missing.\n\nExamples:\n- Default project memory: `project_memory`\n- Monorepo app memory: `apps/api/project_memory`\n- Team convention with shared docs folder: `docs/atlasmind-memory`\n\nPrefer stable relative paths so onboarding, imports, and automation all resolve the same folder structure."
        },
        "atlasmind.showImportProjectAction": {
          "type": "boolean",
          "default": true,
          "description": "Show the Import Existing Project toolbar action in the AtlasMind Memory view.",
          "markdownDescription": "Show the Import Existing Project toolbar action in the AtlasMind Memory view. Disable this if you want a cleaner sidebar for already-bootstrapped repositories.\n\nExamples:\n- Personal workspace still onboarding projects: `true`\n- Locked-down team workspace with a standardized import flow handled elsewhere: `false`"
        },
        "atlasmind.toolApprovalMode": {
          "type": "string",
          "default": "ask-on-write",
          "enum": [
            "always-ask",
            "ask-on-write",
            "ask-on-external",
            "allow-safe-readonly"
          ],
          "description": "How AtlasMind requests approval before running tools with side effects or external execution.",
          "markdownDescription": "How AtlasMind requests approval before running tools with side effects or external execution. This is the main safety dial for automation.\n\nModes:\n- `always-ask`: prompt for every tool action\n- `ask-on-write`: allow reads but prompt before writes\n- `ask-on-external`: prompt when leaving the editor boundary, such as terminal or network activity\n- `allow-safe-readonly`: allow only safe read operations without prompts\n\nExamples:\n- Highly regulated repo: `always-ask`\n- Normal coding workflow: `ask-on-write`\n- Trusted internal automation with careful review: `ask-on-external`\n- Read-only investigation or audits: `allow-safe-readonly`"
        },
        "atlasmind.allowTerminalWrite": {
          "type": "boolean",
          "default": false,
          "description": "Allow write-capable terminal subprocesses such as installs and commits after explicit approval.",
          "markdownDescription": "Allow write-capable terminal subprocesses such as installs and commits after explicit approval. This controls whether AtlasMind may use terminal-based commands that can mutate the workspace or repository.\n\nExamples:\n- Investigation-only mode: `false`\n- Developer sandbox where installs and generators are expected: `true`\n\nKeep this off in repositories where package installation, generated files, or git history changes must go through separate review controls."
        },
        "atlasmind.autoVerifyAfterWrite": {
          "type": "boolean",
          "default": true,
          "description": "Run configured verification scripts after successful workspace write tools such as file-edit, file-write, and git-apply-patch.",
          "markdownDescription": "Run configured verification scripts after successful workspace write tools such as file-edit, file-write, and git-apply-patch. This helps catch regressions immediately after AtlasMind changes files.\n\nExamples:\n- Tight local loop: `true` with `autoVerifyScripts` set to `[\"test\"]`\n- Large monorepo where verification is handled elsewhere: `false`\n- CI-like local enforcement: `true` with multiple scripts such as `test`, `lint`, and `typecheck`"
        },
        "atlasmind.autoVerifyScripts": {
          "type": "array",
          "default": [
            "test"
          ],
          "items": {
            "type": "string"
          },
          "description": "Package scripts to run after successful write operations. Script names are sanitized and invoked without shell interpolation.",
          "markdownDescription": "Package scripts to run after successful write operations. AtlasMind runs these as package scripts, not arbitrary shell fragments.\n\nExamples:\n- Minimal verification: `[\"test\"]`\n- Typical TypeScript project: `[\"lint\", \"test\", \"compile\"]`\n- Scaled repo with dedicated validation scripts: `[\"test:unit\", \"test:manifest\", \"typecheck\"]`\n\nUse short, deterministic scripts that give fast signal after edits."
        },
        "atlasmind.testingPolicyOverride": {
          "type": "string",
          "default": "",
          "description": "Optional override label for the Project Dashboard testing-policy card.",
          "markdownDescription": "Optional override label for the Project Dashboard Testing policy card. Leave this empty to use AtlasMind's default Red-Green TDD policy summary.\n\nExamples:\n- Default Atlas policy: ``\n- Team wording: `Red-Green-Refactor`\n- Alternative policy label: `Behavior-first verification`\n\nThis only changes the displayed policy label; it does not weaken AtlasMind's actual safety and verification guardrails."
        },
        "atlasmind.autoVerifyTimeoutMs": {
          "type": "number",
          "default": 120000,
          "minimum": 5000,
          "description": "Maximum time in milliseconds allowed for each automatic verification script.",
          "markdownDescription": "Maximum time in milliseconds allowed for each automatic verification script. This timeout applies per script.\n\nExamples:\n- Fast local unit checks: `30000`\n- Mixed test and lint pipeline: `120000`\n- Large workspace with slower build validation: `300000`\n\nRaise this only when your verification scripts are intentionally slower and still provide useful post-edit feedback."
        },
        "atlasmind.chatSessionTurnLimit": {
          "type": "number",
          "default": 6,
          "minimum": 1,
          "description": "How many recent chat turns AtlasMind carries forward into freeform requests.",
          "markdownDescription": "How many recent chat turns AtlasMind carries forward into freeform requests. Higher values preserve more conversational continuity but increase prompt size.\n\nExamples:\n- Short, task-focused chats: `4`\n- Default general use: `6`\n- Long debugging sessions where prior decisions matter: `10` or higher\n\nIncrease this carefully in large team sessions so context remains relevant rather than noisy."
        },
        "atlasmind.chatSessionContextChars": {
          "type": "number",
          "default": 2500,
          "minimum": 400,
          "description": "Maximum number of characters reserved for compacted session carry-forward context.",
          "markdownDescription": "Maximum number of characters reserved for compacted session carry-forward context. This acts as the budget for summarized prior conversation.\n\nExamples:\n- Lightweight carry-forward: `1200`\n- Default balance: `2500`\n- Complex multi-step work with many assumptions to preserve: `4000` to `6000`\n\nUse a higher value only if older conversation state is materially affecting correctness."
        },
        "atlasmind.projectApprovalFileThreshold": {
          "type": "number",
          "default": 12,
          "minimum": 1,
          "description": "Estimated changed-file threshold that triggers /project approval gating.",
          "markdownDescription": "Estimated changed-file threshold that triggers `/project` approval gating. AtlasMind uses this with other planner heuristics to decide when work is large enough to require explicit confirmation.\n\nExamples:\n- Small utility repo: `6`\n- Default general-use threshold: `12`\n- Monorepo where broader edits are normal: `20` or `30`\n\nLower this in high-risk repositories where even moderate file churn should pause for review."
        },
        "atlasmind.projectEstimatedFilesPerSubtask": {
          "type": "number",
          "default": 2,
          "minimum": 1,
          "description": "Heuristic multiplier used to estimate changed files from the planned subtask count.",
          "markdownDescription": "Heuristic multiplier used to estimate changed files from the planned subtask count. Higher values make AtlasMind assume each subtask fans out across more files.\n\nExamples:\n- Tightly scoped codebase with isolated modules: `1`\n- Typical service or extension repo: `2`\n- Shared-platform or layered monorepo: `3` or `4`\n\nTune this to match how often a single planned step touches tests, docs, configs, and implementation together."
        },
        "atlasmind.projectChangedFileReferenceLimit": {
          "type": "number",
          "default": 5,
          "minimum": 1,
          "description": "Maximum number of changed files surfaced as clickable references after /project runs.",
          "markdownDescription": "Maximum number of changed files surfaced as clickable references after `/project` runs. This affects summary readability, not the actual set of changed files.\n\nExamples:\n- Compact summaries: `3`\n- Default balance: `5`\n- Review-heavy workflows where users want more direct navigation: `10`\n\nKeep this lower if `/project` runs often touch many files and you want summaries to stay concise."
        },
        "atlasmind.projectRunReportFolder": {
          "type": "string",
          "default": "project_memory/operations",
          "description": "Relative folder for persisted /project run summary JSON reports.",
          "markdownDescription": "Relative folder for persisted `/project` run summary JSON reports. AtlasMind stores operational summaries here for later review or tooling.\n\nExamples:\n- Default operational history: `project_memory/operations`\n- Separate audit folder inside docs: `docs/atlasmind/runs`\n- Centralized automation folder in a monorepo: `ops/atlasmind/run-reports`\n\nChoose a stable relative path that fits your repo's review and retention practices."
        },
        "atlasmind.projectDependencyMonitoringEnabled": {
          "type": "boolean",
          "default": true,
          "description": "Scaffold dependency monitoring defaults when AtlasMind bootstraps governance files for a project.",
          "markdownDescription": "Scaffold dependency monitoring defaults when AtlasMind bootstraps governance files for a project. This controls whether bootstrap adds dependency-update automation and SSOT policy starter docs for Atlas-built repositories.\n\nExamples:\n- Team template repo where AtlasMind should always wire dependency review automation: `true`\n- Minimal experimental repo where governance files stay manual: `false`\n\nDisable this if your organization already provisions dependency automation elsewhere and you do not want AtlasMind creating update-policy files."
        },
        "atlasmind.projectDependencyMonitoringProviders": {
          "type": "array",
          "default": [
            "dependabot"
          ],
          "items": {
            "type": "string",
            "enum": [
              "dependabot",
              "renovate",
              "snyk",
              "azure-devops"
            ]
          },
          "description": "Dependency monitoring providers AtlasMind should scaffold for project governance baselines.",
          "markdownDescription": "Dependency monitoring providers AtlasMind should scaffold for project governance baselines. AtlasMind currently supports Dependabot, Renovate, Snyk, and Azure DevOps-oriented pipeline scaffolding because those patterns are common in professional repositories and can be represented safely as checked-in config.\n\nExamples:\n- GitHub-native default: `[\"dependabot\"]`\n- Organizations standardized on Renovate: `[\"renovate\"]`\n- Security-driven workflow with Snyk plus Dependabot: `[\"dependabot\", \"snyk\"]`\n- Mixed enterprise rollout: `[\"dependabot\", \"renovate\", \"azure-devops\"]`\n\nIf this list is empty while dependency monitoring is enabled, AtlasMind still scaffolds SSOT policy docs so teams can document a manual or externally managed review workflow."
        },
        "atlasmind.projectDependencyMonitoringSchedule": {
          "type": "string",
          "default": "weekly",
          "enum": [
            "daily",
            "weekly",
            "monthly"
          ],
          "description": "Default cadence AtlasMind uses when scaffolding dependency monitoring automation.",
          "markdownDescription": "Default cadence AtlasMind uses when scaffolding dependency monitoring automation. AtlasMind maps this into the generated Dependabot or Renovate configuration for Atlas-built projects.\n\nExamples:\n- Fast-moving security-sensitive services: `daily`\n- Normal team workflow with predictable review windows: `weekly`\n- Stable products that prefer fewer update PRs: `monthly`\n\nChoose the slowest cadence that still lets your team review important updates before they become risky backlog."
        },
        "atlasmind.projectDependencyMonitoringIssueTemplate": {
          "type": "boolean",
          "default": true,
          "description": "Add a dependency review issue template when AtlasMind scaffolds project governance files.",
          "markdownDescription": "Add a dependency review issue template when AtlasMind scaffolds project governance files. The template helps teams record approval decisions, exceptions, and follow-up work after automation detects dependency drift.\n\nExamples:\n- Review-heavy engineering org that tracks every deferred or major update: `true`\n- Lightweight personal repo with no formal review tickets: `false`\n\nKeep this on when updates must be reviewed by multiple people or linked to compliance evidence."
        },
        "atlasmind.toolWebhookEnabled": {
          "type": "boolean",
          "default": false,
          "description": "Enable outbound webhook delivery for Atlas tool execution events.",
          "markdownDescription": "Enable outbound webhook delivery for Atlas tool execution events. When enabled, AtlasMind sends selected tool lifecycle events to the configured webhook endpoint.\n\nExamples:\n- Local-only development with no external observers: `false`\n- Team telemetry or audit pipeline: `true`\n\nOnly enable this when you have an approved HTTPS endpoint and clear expectations about what execution metadata may leave the editor."
        },
        "atlasmind.toolWebhookUrl": {
          "type": "string",
          "default": "",
          "description": "HTTPS endpoint that receives Atlas tool execution webhook payloads.",
          "markdownDescription": "HTTPS endpoint that receives Atlas tool execution webhook payloads. Leave empty unless `atlasmind.toolWebhookEnabled` is turned on.\n\nExamples:\n- Internal event collector: `https://ops.example.com/atlasmind/webhooks`\n- Local integration test tunnel: `https://1234abcd.ngrok.app/hooks/atlasmind`\n\nPrefer a dedicated ingestion endpoint for scaled deployments so AtlasMind events stay separated from unrelated webhooks."
        },
        "atlasmind.toolWebhookTimeoutMs": {
          "type": "number",
          "default": 5000,
          "minimum": 1000,
          "description": "Webhook request timeout in milliseconds.",
          "markdownDescription": "Webhook request timeout in milliseconds. This limits how long AtlasMind waits for the webhook receiver before treating delivery as timed out.\n\nExamples:\n- Low-latency internal service: `3000`\n- Default general use: `5000`\n- Cross-region or heavily filtered ingress path: `10000`\n\nDo not raise this unnecessarily, or slow webhook infrastructure can start delaying the editor experience."
        },
        "atlasmind.toolWebhookEvents": {
          "type": "array",
          "default": [
            "tool.started",
            "tool.completed",
            "tool.failed"
          ],
          "items": {
            "type": "string",
            "enum": [
              "tool.started",
              "tool.completed",
              "tool.failed",
              "tool.test"
            ]
          },
          "description": "Selected tool webhook event names to emit.",
          "markdownDescription": "Selected tool webhook event names to emit. Choose the smallest set that satisfies your observability or audit needs.\n\nAvailable events:\n- `tool.started`\n- `tool.completed`\n- `tool.failed`\n- `tool.test`\n\nExamples:\n- Minimal audit trail: `[\"tool.failed\"]`\n- Basic lifecycle monitoring: `[\"tool.started\", \"tool.completed\", \"tool.failed\"]`\n- Integration testing of receivers: include `tool.test` temporarily"
        },
        "atlasmind.experimentalSkillLearningEnabled": {
          "type": "boolean",
          "default": false,
          "description": "Enable Atlas-generated custom skill drafts. Warning: this sends additional model requests and generated code still requires manual safety review.",
          "markdownDescription": "Enable Atlas-generated custom skill drafts. This feature increases model usage and the generated artifacts still require manual review before they are trusted or committed.\n\nExamples:\n- Production or regulated workspace: `false`\n- Sandbox for experimenting with new skills: `true`\n\nTreat this as an assisted authoring feature, not an autonomous trust boundary."
        },
        "atlasmind.dailyCostLimitUsd": {
          "type": "number",
          "default": 0,
          "minimum": 0,
          "description": "Daily cost limit in USD. Set to 0 to disable. AtlasMind will warn you when 80% and 100% of this limit is reached.",
          "markdownDescription": "Daily cost limit in USD. Set this to `0` to disable the cap. AtlasMind warns at 80% usage and again at 100%.\n\nExamples:\n- Unlimited personal experimentation: `0`\n- Individual guardrail for a paid account: `5` or `10`\n- Shared team budget with tighter daily control per developer: `20` or another agreed cap\n\nUse this with `budgetMode` to combine soft routing preferences and a hard spend boundary."
        },
        "atlasmind.voice.ttsEnabled": {
          "type": "boolean",
          "default": false,
          "description": "Automatically speak @atlas freeform responses aloud using the Voice Panel TTS engine.",
          "markdownDescription": "Automatically speak `@atlas` freeform responses aloud using the Voice Panel TTS engine. This affects spoken playback, not text generation.\n\nExamples:\n- Hands-free coding or accessibility workflow: `true`\n- Quiet office or text-only use: `false`"
        },
        "atlasmind.voice.sttEnabled": {
          "type": "boolean",
          "default": false,
          "description": "Show a voice input button in the Voice Panel (STT requires microphone access).",
          "markdownDescription": "Show a voice input button in the Voice Panel. Speech-to-text requires microphone access and browser or platform support.\n\nExamples:\n- Voice-first workflow: `true`\n- Locked-down desktop without microphone permissions: `false`"
        },
        "atlasmind.voice.rate": {
          "type": "number",
          "default": 1,
          "minimum": 0.5,
          "maximum": 2.0,
          "description": "Speech synthesis rate. 1.0 is normal speed; 0.5 is half speed; 2.0 is double speed.",
          "markdownDescription": "Speech synthesis rate. `1.0` is normal speed, `0.5` is half speed, and `2.0` is double speed.\n\nExamples:\n- Accessibility or careful listening: `0.8`\n- Default conversational playback: `1.0`\n- Fast review of long responses: `1.25` or `1.5`"
        },
        "atlasmind.voice.pitch": {
          "type": "number",
          "default": 1,
          "minimum": 0,
          "maximum": 2.0,
          "description": "Speech synthesis pitch. 1.0 is the default pitch.",
          "markdownDescription": "Speech synthesis pitch. `1.0` is the default pitch for the selected voice.\n\nExamples:\n- Lower, flatter speech profile: `0.8`\n- Default voice output: `1.0`\n- Brighter or more animated playback: `1.2`\n\nUse this mainly for comfort and intelligibility rather than correctness."
        },
        "atlasmind.voice.volume": {
          "type": "number",
          "default": 1,
          "minimum": 0,
          "maximum": 1.0,
          "description": "Speech synthesis volume (0 = silent, 1 = full volume).",
          "markdownDescription": "Speech synthesis volume where `0` is silent and `1` is full volume.\n\nExamples:\n- Shared office or quiet environment: `0.3` to `0.5`\n- Normal headset use: `0.8` to `1.0`\n- Muted while keeping TTS enabled for quick toggling: `0`"
        },
        "atlasmind.voice.language": {
          "type": "string",
          "default": "",
          "description": "BCP 47 language tag for voice synthesis and recognition (e.g. 'en-US', 'fr-FR'). Leave empty to use the browser/OS default.",
          "markdownDescription": "BCP 47 language tag for voice synthesis and recognition, such as `en-US` or `fr-FR`. Leave empty to use the browser or OS default.\n\nExamples:\n- US English: `en-US`\n- British English: `en-GB`\n- French (France): `fr-FR`\n- Default system language: empty string\n\nSet this explicitly in shared environments where predictable voice language matters."
        },
        "atlasmind.maxToolIterations": {
          "type": "number",
          "default": 10,
          "minimum": 1,
          "maximum": 50,
          "description": "Maximum tool-call loop iterations per agent turn.",
          "markdownDescription": "Maximum tool-call loop iterations per agent turn. This limits how many sequential rounds of tool use the agent can perform before it must stop and answer.\n\nExamples:\n- Conservative environment: `5`\n- Default balance: `10`\n- Complex workflows that genuinely need longer tool chains: `15` to `20`\n\nRaise this carefully, because higher values can increase latency and unintended automation depth."
        },
        "atlasmind.maxToolCallsPerTurn": {
          "type": "number",
          "default": 8,
          "minimum": 1,
          "maximum": 30,
          "description": "Maximum parallel tool calls the model may issue in a single turn.",
          "markdownDescription": "Maximum parallel tool calls the model may issue in a single turn. This caps fan-out when the model wants to gather or verify data quickly.\n\nExamples:\n- Minimal concurrency for predictable behavior: `3`\n- Default general use: `8`\n- Large codebase exploration with many independent reads: `12` or `16`\n\nHigher values can improve speed for read-heavy work but may produce noisier or more expensive turns."
        },
        "atlasmind.toolExecutionTimeoutMs": {
          "type": "number",
          "default": 15000,
          "minimum": 1000,
          "description": "Per-tool execution timeout in milliseconds.",
          "markdownDescription": "Per-tool execution timeout in milliseconds. If a tool call exceeds this limit, AtlasMind treats it as timed out.\n\nExamples:\n- Very fast local commands only: `5000`\n- Default mixed workload: `15000`\n- Slower file-system or network-backed tools: `30000`\n\nTune this alongside tool approval and webhook settings so slow integrations do not degrade the interactive experience."
        },
        "atlasmind.providerTimeoutMs": {
          "type": "number",
          "default": 30000,
          "minimum": 5000,
          "description": "Maximum time in milliseconds to wait for a model provider response.",
          "markdownDescription": "Maximum time in milliseconds to wait for a model provider response. This covers the provider round-trip, not local tool execution.\n\nExamples:\n- Fast local or LAN-hosted models: `15000`\n- Default cloud-provider balance: `30000`\n- Slower premium reasoning models or distant regions: `45000` to `60000`\n\nUse a higher timeout when you intentionally allow slower reasoning models through `speedMode` or provider-specific routing."
        }
      }
    }
  },
  "scripts": {
    "vscode:prepublish": "npm run compile",
    "compile": "tsc -p ./",
    "watch": "tsc -watch -p ./",
    "cli": "node ./out/cli/main.js",
    "monitor:integrations": "node .github/scripts/check-integration-drift.mjs",
    "monitor:integrations:update": "node .github/scripts/check-integration-drift.mjs --write",
